[ðŸ› Bug]: Navigation to timed out as no request payload was received
### Have you read the Contributing Guidelines on issues?

- [x] I have read the [Contributing Guidelines on issues](https://github.com/webdriverio/webdriverio/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#reporting-new-issues).

### WebdriverIO Version

latest

### Node.js Version

18.20.0

### Mode

Standalone Mode

### Which capabilities are you using?

```typescript
{
    browserName: 'chrome',
    browserVersion: '128.0',

    webSocketUrl: true,
}
```

### What happened?

I get an error like `Navigation to 'https://webdriver.io' timed out as no request payload was received` when create session in master process and then attach to it from worker.

### What is your expected behavior?

I expect that url will open without any error in my case.

### How to reproduce the bug.

```js
// wdio-master.js

const cp = require("child_process");
const path = require('path');
const { remote } = require('webdriverio');

const worker = cp.fork(path.join(process.cwd(), './wdio-worker'));

let client;

(async function () {
    client = await remote({
        protocol: 'http',
        hostname: '127.0.0.1',
        port: 4444,
        path: '/wd/hub',

        logLevel: 'debug',

        capabilities: {
            browserName: 'chrome',
            browserVersion: '128.0',

            webSocketUrl: true,
        }
    });

    worker.send({browser: client, options: client.options});

    worker.on('message', async () => {
        await client.deleteSession();
        process.exit(0);
    });
})()
    .catch(async (e) => {
        console.error(e.stack);
        await client.deleteSession();
        process.exit(1);
    });
```

```js
// wdio-worker.js

const { attach } = require('webdriverio');

process.on('message', async ({browser, options}) => {
    const client = await attach({...options, options, ...browser});

    await client.url('https://webdriver.io');

    client.on('log.entryAdded', (entryAdded) => console.log('LOG FROM CONSOLE:', JSON.stringify(entryAdded, null, 4)));
    await client.execute(() => console.log('Hello Bidi'));

    process.send(`worker.${browser.sessionId}.freeBrowser`);
});
```

